00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:29.300 align:middle line:90%
of infrastructure.

00:11:29.300 --> 00:11:31.780 align:middle line:84%
And then they disperse all
their economic activity

00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:33.490 align:middle line:84%
and their housing
and then people

00:11:33.490 --> 00:11:36.100 align:middle line:84%
have to drive around to get
the things they want and work.

00:11:36.100 --> 00:11:38.590 align:middle line:84%
And that leads to huge
pollution, energy use,

00:11:38.590 --> 00:11:39.560 align:middle line:90%
and health issues.

00:11:39.560 --> 00:11:41.170 align:middle line:84%
>> When I first came
to North America,

00:11:41.170 --> 00:11:45.670 align:middle line:84%
it was actually quite a shock
to see how separated uses were.

00:11:45.670 --> 00:11:49.090 align:middle line:84%
The fact that we build these
huge residential subdivisions,

00:11:49.090 --> 00:11:51.700 align:middle line:84%
we build these huge
commercial shopping malls,

00:11:51.700 --> 00:11:54.040 align:middle line:84%
we build these huge
industrial estates,

00:11:54.040 --> 00:11:58.630 align:middle line:84%
and they're separated
and just the volume

00:11:58.630 --> 00:12:03.220 align:middle line:84%
of traffic that generates, and
the fact that really it's very

00:12:03.220 --> 00:12:04.907 align:middle line:90%
difficult to walk anywhere.

00:12:04.907 --> 00:12:10.760 align:middle line:90%


00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:15.940 align:middle line:84%
We have to create ecological
cities where the impacts are

00:12:15.940 --> 00:12:17.680 align:middle line:84%
lower within the
cities themselves,

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:20.200 align:middle line:84%
but also we're not
spreading as much

00:12:20.200 --> 00:12:24.460 align:middle line:84%
into the surrounding landscape
and the surrounding habitats.

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:28.600 align:middle line:84%
>> If not designed well, suburbs
can lead to urban sprawl which

00:12:28.600 --> 00:12:31.930 align:middle line:84%
has a detrimental effect on both
the environment and our sense

00:12:31.930 --> 00:12:35.180 align:middle line:90%
of community.

00:12:35.180 --> 00:12:37.820 align:middle line:84%
While suburbs continue
to quickly expand,

00:12:37.820 --> 00:12:42.270 align:middle line:84%
they aren't the only
housing choice in demand.

00:12:42.270 --> 00:12:45.210 align:middle line:84%
Condominiums have become
a popular housing option

00:12:45.210 --> 00:12:48.670 align:middle line:84%
among both younger
and older generations.

00:12:48.670 --> 00:12:51.480 align:middle line:84%
They can offer proximity to
neighbors and accessibility

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:52.800 align:middle line:90%
to services.

00:12:52.800 --> 00:12:56.340 align:middle line:84%
But can condo living provide
that feeling of community

00:12:56.340 --> 00:13:00.420 align:middle line:84%
that is so essential
to our well being?

00:13:00.420 --> 00:13:03.180 align:middle line:84%
To find out more
about this, I decided

00:13:03.180 --> 00:13:04.650 align:middle line:84%
to meet up with
someone who lives

00:13:04.650 --> 00:13:07.080 align:middle line:90%
in a populated urban area.

00:13:07.080 --> 00:13:08.970 align:middle line:90%
This is Kirsten.

00:13:08.970 --> 00:13:12.870 align:middle line:84%
She lives in a multi-unit
condo building in Vancouver.

00:13:12.870 --> 00:13:15.330 align:middle line:84%
Through our discussions,
she expressed

00:13:15.330 --> 00:13:17.530 align:middle line:84%
that despite being in
a safe neighborhood

00:13:17.530 --> 00:13:21.210 align:middle line:84%
and having modern amenities in
her building, she rarely sees,

00:13:21.210 --> 00:13:24.120 align:middle line:84%
let alone interacts
with her neighbors.

00:13:24.120 --> 00:13:25.980 align:middle line:84%
As a result, feels
like the building

00:13:25.980 --> 00:13:28.260 align:middle line:90%
lacks a sense of community.

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:31.800 align:middle line:84%
>> It's nice to know people when
you're walking down the street

00:13:31.800 --> 00:13:38.760 align:middle line:84%
and have interesting
conversations and sort of be

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:42.360 align:middle line:84%
more connected to your community
rather than just coming

00:13:42.360 --> 00:13:44.790 align:middle line:84%
in and coming out going
to different places,

00:13:44.790 --> 00:13:46.800 align:middle line:84%
living your busy
day-to-day life.

00:13:46.800 --> 00:13:49.320 align:middle line:84%
>> In itself, condominiums
are not the answer.

00:13:49.320 --> 00:13:52.860 align:middle line:84%
And, in fact, they can be part
of the problem of isolation.

00:13:52.860 --> 00:13:55.300 align:middle line:84%
But designed well, they can
be part of the solution.

00:13:55.300 --> 00:13:58.080 align:middle line:84%
So it really is a
question of the quality

00:13:58.080 --> 00:14:01.060 align:middle line:84%
of design both of
the building itself,

00:14:01.060 --> 00:14:03.300 align:middle line:84%
how it relates to the
street and how it relates

00:14:03.300 --> 00:14:05.520 align:middle line:90%
to its surrounding open space.

00:14:05.520 --> 00:14:07.020 align:middle line:84%
There's very little
space for people

00:14:07.020 --> 00:14:10.560 align:middle line:84%
to interact in that kind of
typical apartment building

00:14:10.560 --> 00:14:11.700 align:middle line:90%
or condominium building.

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:16.320 align:middle line:84%
So you come out, you've got
this very black bear corridor,

00:14:16.320 --> 00:14:18.870 align:middle line:84%
you walk to the elevator,
you're down to the parking lot

00:14:18.870 --> 00:14:21.730 align:middle line:84%
usually, you're in your car,
and then you're off to work.

00:14:21.730 --> 00:14:24.330 align:middle line:84%
And so there are
very few places that

00:14:24.330 --> 00:14:28.920 align:middle line:84%
are designed for intentionally
congregating and mixing

00:14:28.920 --> 00:14:30.090 align:middle line:90%
and bumping into people.

00:14:30.090 --> 00:14:32.520 align:middle line:10%
>> I don't know that we've
designed our high rises well

00:14:32.520 --> 00:14:36.030 align:middle line:10%
enough to encourage
that form of community.

00:14:36.030 --> 00:14:38.670 align:middle line:84%
Often people see each
other as kind of they

00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:42.240 align:middle line:84%
have to line up behind others
to get on the elevator.

00:14:42.240 --> 00:14:44.730 align:middle line:84%
And we don't have the right
kind of common spaces.

00:14:44.730 --> 00:14:47.370 align:middle line:84%
Even if you wanted to
borrow sugar from the person

00:14:47.370 --> 00:14:50.550 align:middle line:84%
downstairs, you have to phone in
and get security clearance just

00:14:50.550 --> 00:14:52.230 align:middle line:84%
to go down to the
next door neighbor.

00:14:52.230 --> 00:14:56.190 align:middle line:84%
>> We've heard the thing,
fences make great neighbors.

00:14:56.190 --> 00:14:59.670 align:middle line:84%
And it's kind of like as long
as I know what my space is,

00:14:59.670 --> 00:15:01.290 align:middle line:84%
I'll interact and
engage with you.

00:15:01.290 --> 00:15:03.100 align:middle line:90%
But you've got to know my space.

00:15:03.100 --> 00:15:05.850 align:middle line:84%
And I wonder if an apartment
that doesn't work that way.

00:15:05.850 --> 00:15:09.270 align:middle line:84%
>> We're not imposing solitary
confinement on people,

00:15:09.270 --> 00:15:12.570 align:middle line:84%
but we are designing places that
make it difficult to interact

00:15:12.570 --> 00:15:16.210 align:middle line:84%
with people, which amounts
to a similar thing.

00:15:16.210 --> 00:15:19.440 align:middle line:84%
So through design we're
creating isolation

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:20.910 align:middle line:90%
and we're creating separation.

00:15:20.910 --> 00:15:24.960 align:middle line:84%
>> I ask people, how many
of you know your neighbor?

00:15:24.960 --> 00:15:28.350 align:middle line:84%
There it's usually about a
half now their neighbors.

00:15:28.350 --> 00:15:30.810 align:middle line:84%
I ask, how many of you know
the last name of your neighbor?

00:15:30.810 --> 00:15:32.605 align:middle line:90%
And it's probably 10%.

00:15:32.605 --> 00:15:34.980 align:middle line:84%
>> Would you happen to know
any of your neighbors on that

00:15:34.980 --> 00:15:35.805 align:middle line:90%
street?

00:15:35.805 --> 00:15:37.230 align:middle line:90%
>> I do not at this point.

00:15:37.230 --> 00:15:38.950 align:middle line:84%
I've lived there
for about six weeks,

00:15:38.950 --> 00:15:40.960 align:middle line:84%
and I know the gentleman
that lives below me.

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:41.760 align:middle line:90%
That's about it.

00:15:41.760 --> 00:15:45.760 align:middle line:84%
>> In my apartment building,
people don't even like make eye

00:15:45.760 --> 00:15:46.560 align:middle line:90%
contact with me.

00:15:46.560 --> 00:15:47.977 align:middle line:84%
When I pass them
at the hall, they

00:15:47.977 --> 00:15:51.765 align:middle line:84%
look away instead of trying
to even give a basic greeting.

00:15:51.765 --> 00:15:54.450 align:middle line:84%
>> Even the further you go up,
the further high you're living,

00:15:54.450 --> 00:15:57.940 align:middle line:84%
the further detached you
are from your community,

00:15:57.940 --> 00:16:00.510 align:middle line:84%
for example, or
anybody around you.

00:16:00.510 --> 00:16:03.720 align:middle line:84%
>> It's very important, I
think, that sense of community

00:16:03.720 --> 00:16:06.640 align:middle line:84%
and the security that brings
when you know people who are

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:07.440 align:middle line:90%
around you.

00:16:07.440 --> 00:16:08.773 align:middle line:90%
>> What do you mean by security?

00:16:08.773 --> 00:16:10.560 align:middle line:84%
>> If you don't
know your neighbors,

00:16:10.560 --> 00:16:12.480 align:middle line:84%
you don't know what
kind of people they are.

00:16:12.480 --> 00:16:14.280 align:middle line:84%
>> I don't even think I'm
going to live in this community

00:16:14.280 --> 00:16:15.480 align:middle line:90%
for more than a year or two.

00:16:15.480 --> 00:16:17.078 align:middle line:84%
So maybe when I'm
a little bit older,

00:16:17.078 --> 00:16:18.870 align:middle line:84%
I have a family, kids,
and everything else,

00:16:18.870 --> 00:16:19.870 align:middle line:90%
then it'll be important.

00:16:19.870 --> 00:16:21.450 align:middle line:84%
But for right now,
I'd rather just

00:16:21.450 --> 00:16:23.825 align:middle line:84%
communicate with the people
that I find important in life

00:16:23.825 --> 00:16:26.967 align:middle line:84%
rather than helping
a community or trying

00:16:26.967 --> 00:16:28.800 align:middle line:84%
to work on a community
that I might not even

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:30.430 align:middle line:90%
live in in a year from now.

00:16:30.430 --> 00:16:32.460 align:middle line:84%
>> I mean, Winston
Churchill famously said,

00:16:32.460 --> 00:16:35.460 align:middle line:84%
we shape our buildings, and
then our buildings shape us.

00:16:35.460 --> 00:16:38.280 align:middle line:84%
The same is true of our
cities and our neighborhoods.

00:16:38.280 --> 00:16:39.570 align:middle line:90%
We shape our neighborhoods.

00:16:39.570 --> 00:16:42.330 align:middle line:84%
We shape our cities, and then
our cities shape us back.

00:16:42.330 --> 00:16:44.730 align:middle line:84%
And so in many
ways, our cities are

00:16:44.730 --> 00:16:48.990 align:middle line:84%
a reflection of our thinking and
our culture and our paradigms,

00:16:48.990 --> 00:16:51.270 align:middle line:84%
if you like, about
how we see the world

00:16:51.270 --> 00:16:54.370 align:middle line:84%
and how we see our relationship
amongst each other.

00:16:54.370 --> 00:16:59.050 align:middle line:84%
>> We no longer
have front porches.

00:16:59.050 --> 00:17:00.580 align:middle line:84%
Now, I don't know
why that happened.

00:17:00.580 --> 00:17:05.800 align:middle line:84%
Was it the garage that took over
the front porch and the fact

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:09.460 align:middle line:84%
that people like to just drive
in, close the door behind them?

00:17:09.460 --> 00:17:12.339 align:middle line:84%
But what that means is that
when people are going for walks,

00:17:12.339 --> 00:17:14.380 align:middle line:84%
they don't see one
another anymore.

00:17:14.380 --> 00:17:17.109 align:middle line:84%
Front yards are
often just lawns.

00:17:17.109 --> 00:17:22.089 align:middle line:84%
Our backyards are where we
often create the greatest oasis,

00:17:22.089 --> 00:17:25.690 align:middle line:84%
and so we don't-- we don't have
a natural connection with one

00:17:25.690 --> 00:17:26.859 align:middle line:90%
another.

00:17:26.859 --> 00:17:29.980 align:middle line:84%
And then eventually, other
things start to break down.

00:17:29.980 --> 00:17:34.150 align:middle line:84%
>> If you feel connected to your
neighborhood, to your place,

00:17:34.150 --> 00:17:36.460 align:middle line:84%
you feel like it's
your community.

00:17:36.460 --> 00:17:38.050 align:middle line:84%
If you don't feel
connected to it,

00:17:38.050 --> 00:17:41.080 align:middle line:84%
you feel like it's just
a place where you live.

00:17:41.080 --> 00:17:44.740 align:middle line:84%
If you feel connected to the
people in that neighborhood,

00:17:44.740 --> 00:17:47.080 align:middle line:84%
you feel like those
people are your community.

00:17:47.080 --> 00:17:49.240 align:middle line:84%
If you don't, you probably
feel like your community

00:17:49.240 --> 00:17:51.520 align:middle line:84%
are actually a group
of people spread

00:17:51.520 --> 00:17:54.440 align:middle line:84%
throughout the city who are
your friends and acquaintances.

00:17:54.440 --> 00:17:58.210 align:middle line:84%
>> And you're seeing this
renewal all around the world

00:17:58.210 --> 00:18:01.000 align:middle line:84%
where neighborhoods are
becoming far more important,

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:06.280 align:middle line:84%
both in city planning but also
just citizens saying I want

00:18:06.280 --> 00:18:07.210 align:middle line:90%
to know my neighbor.

00:18:07.210 --> 00:18:09.730 align:middle line:84%
I want to be in a
neighborhood that's safe.

00:18:09.730 --> 00:18:12.160 align:middle line:84%
I want to be in a
place that's fun.

00:18:12.160 --> 00:18:15.040 align:middle line:90%
And it's good for me.

00:18:15.040 --> 00:18:19.220 align:middle line:84%
It's great for my
kids and guess what

00:18:19.220 --> 00:18:22.648 align:middle line:84%
neighborhoods with a sense of
community land values go up.

00:18:22.648 --> 00:18:24.190 align:middle line:84%
>> Lots of people
are realizing that.

00:18:24.190 --> 00:18:26.020 align:middle line:84%
And what's happening is
actually those places

00:18:26.020 --> 00:18:27.190 align:middle line:90%
are becoming more expensive.

00:18:27.190 --> 00:18:28.390 align:middle line:90%
They're becoming gentrified.

00:18:28.390 --> 00:18:32.020 align:middle line:84%
They're becoming the most
popular spaces in cities.

00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:34.720 align:middle line:84%
We're actually underproviding
those kind of places

00:18:34.720 --> 00:18:36.860 align:middle line:90%
right now in a big way.

00:18:36.860 --> 00:18:39.610 align:middle line:84%
And it's what's driving
the lack of affordability

00:18:39.610 --> 00:18:42.220 align:middle line:84%
in many of our world
cities like Vancouver,

00:18:42.220 --> 00:18:44.090 align:middle line:84%
like San Francisco,
like New York,

00:18:44.090 --> 00:18:46.930 align:middle line:84%
London because people
are really demanding

00:18:46.930 --> 00:18:50.020 align:middle line:84%
the neighborhoods that
are mixed use and have

00:18:50.020 --> 00:18:53.350 align:middle line:84%
that public amenity, that
public open space, and then

00:18:53.350 --> 00:18:54.387 align:middle line:90%
great urban design.

00:18:54.387 --> 00:18:55.720 align:middle line:90%
>> We've been looking at houses.

00:18:55.720 --> 00:18:58.540 align:middle line:84%
And like why be in this little
cookie-cutter neighborhood

00:18:58.540 --> 00:19:00.820 align:middle line:90%
where maybe you're like--

00:19:00.820 --> 00:19:02.700 align:middle line:84%
>> Two people in a
6,000 square foot house?

00:19:02.700 --> 00:19:02.960 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, it's ridiculous.

00:19:02.960 --> 00:19:03.880 align:middle line:90%
>> It's completely ridiculous.

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:05.588 align:middle line:84%
>> But it's like no
one needs that space,

00:19:05.588 --> 00:19:06.770 align:middle line:90%
but you need people.

00:19:06.770 --> 00:19:09.880 align:middle line:84%
>> Although we are
social beings by nature,

00:19:09.880 --> 00:19:13.270 align:middle line:84%
it's been reported that one
third of Americans never reach

00:19:13.270 --> 00:19:16.360 align:middle line:84%
out to their neighbors, and more
and more people are choosing

00:19:16.360 --> 00:19:18.310 align:middle line:90%
to live alone.

00:19:18.310 --> 00:19:20.110 align:middle line:84%
Since the design
of our communities

00:19:20.110 --> 00:19:23.530 align:middle line:84%
can hinder opportunities for
interaction, which negatively

00:19:23.530 --> 00:19:26.710 align:middle line:84%
affects our being, it
becomes vitally important

00:19:26.710 --> 00:19:28.630 align:middle line:84%
that we create our
own opportunities

00:19:28.630 --> 00:19:29.800 align:middle line:90%
to connect with others.

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:32.452 align:middle line:90%


00:19:32.452 --> 00:19:34.660 align:middle line:84%
>> Being a part of one's
community is very rewarding,

00:19:34.660 --> 00:19:35.740 align:middle line:90%
but it can also--

00:19:35.740 --> 00:19:37.870 align:middle line:84%
it's not-- it's not
always easy to get

00:19:37.870 --> 00:19:40.660 align:middle line:84%
involved when you yourself
have been at the outskirts.

00:19:40.660 --> 00:19:43.010 align:middle line:84%
But I do think that's one
of the most reliable routes

00:19:43.010 --> 00:19:43.810 align:middle line:90%
to happiness.

00:19:43.810 --> 00:19:47.620 align:middle line:84%
>> When I move into a condo,
I'm going to organize my floor

00:19:47.620 --> 00:19:51.520 align:middle line:84%
first, and then I'm going to
start to organize the whole

00:19:51.520 --> 00:19:52.910 align:middle line:90%
building.

00:19:52.910 --> 00:19:55.810 align:middle line:84%
But if I can get
my floor organized

00:19:55.810 --> 00:19:59.140 align:middle line:84%
and people hear us having
fun and suddenly they

00:19:59.140 --> 00:20:03.280 align:middle line:84%
hear from others, gee, if
you lived on floor nine, what

00:20:03.280 --> 00:20:05.770 align:middle line:84%
a great time you'd
have, I wish I

00:20:05.770 --> 00:20:09.460 align:middle line:90%
could have that kind of floor.

00:20:09.460 --> 00:20:11.530 align:middle line:84%
That's what I think
it takes, ultimately.

00:20:11.530 --> 00:20:15.280 align:middle line:84%
>> I think that there's a lot
of interesting people here that

00:20:15.280 --> 00:20:20.050 align:middle line:84%
I'd like to get to know more,
and I think that we kind

00:20:20.050 --> 00:20:24.520 align:middle line:84%
of take for granted the
situation that we live

00:20:24.520 --> 00:20:26.562 align:middle line:84%
in because I think that
the building is so cool.

00:20:26.562 --> 00:20:27.520 align:middle line:90%
The rooftop is so cool.

00:20:27.520 --> 00:20:31.060 align:middle line:84%
If we could have monthly
gatherings or more

00:20:31.060 --> 00:20:34.900 align:middle line:84%
regular get-togethers I think
that would be really nice.

00:20:34.900 --> 00:20:37.720 align:middle line:84%
>> Surveys report that
when buying a condo,

00:20:37.720 --> 00:20:41.050 align:middle line:84%
amenities like rooftop patios
and party rooms are in high

00:20:41.050 --> 00:20:42.220 align:middle line:90%
demand.

00:20:42.220 --> 00:20:44.560 align:middle line:84%
But how often do we
really see these spaces

00:20:44.560 --> 00:20:47.450 align:middle line:90%
being used to socialize?

00:20:47.450 --> 00:20:50.360 align:middle line:84%
Wanting to help Kirsten to
get to know her neighbors

00:20:50.360 --> 00:20:53.630 align:middle line:84%
and wanting to make use of
the building's common spaces,

00:20:53.630 --> 00:20:58.300 align:middle line:84%
I convinced her to throw a party
on the rooftop of her condo.

00:20:58.300 --> 00:20:59.300 align:middle line:90%
>> Kirsten, how are you?

00:20:59.300 --> 00:21:02.020 align:middle line:90%
It's Tamaran.

00:21:02.020 --> 00:21:02.840 align:middle line:90%
How are you doing?

00:21:02.840 --> 00:21:04.930 align:middle line:84%
How are you feeling
about the dates?

00:21:04.930 --> 00:21:06.370 align:middle line:84%
Which date worked
better for you?

00:21:06.370 --> 00:21:09.285 align:middle line:10%
And let's take it from that?

00:21:09.285 --> 00:21:11.410 align:middle line:84%
Essentially, you invite
people, and they just come.

00:21:11.410 --> 00:21:12.785 align:middle line:84%
And it can be like
standing room.

00:21:12.785 --> 00:21:15.610 align:middle line:90%
