One study reported
that 70% of women

00:31:50.070 --> 00:31:52.260 align:middle line:84%
believe that smartphones
were negatively

00:31:52.260 --> 00:31:54.720 align:middle line:90%
impacting their relationships.

00:31:54.720 --> 00:31:58.620 align:middle line:84%
There's even a term for
this interference fubbing,

00:31:58.620 --> 00:32:03.240 align:middle line:84%
which is defined as snubbing
a person in favor of a phone.

00:32:03.240 --> 00:32:07.260 align:middle line:84%
To no one's surprise, the
more we engage in fubbing,

00:32:07.260 --> 00:32:12.710 align:middle line:84%
the less available we are
to the people around us.

00:32:12.710 --> 00:32:16.490 align:middle line:84%
And the same can be true
for online interactions.

00:32:16.490 --> 00:32:19.130 align:middle line:84%
As Sherry Turkle
states, the ties

00:32:19.130 --> 00:32:21.470 align:middle line:84%
we form through the
internet are not

00:32:21.470 --> 00:32:25.160 align:middle line:90%
in the end the ties that bind.

00:32:25.160 --> 00:32:30.590 align:middle line:84%
>> Texting, email, posting, all
of these things let us present

00:32:30.590 --> 00:32:32.870 align:middle line:90%
the self as we want to be.

00:32:32.870 --> 00:32:37.850 align:middle line:84%
We get to edit, and that
means we get to delete.

00:32:37.850 --> 00:32:43.250 align:middle line:84%
And that means we get to retouch
the face, the voice, the flesh,

00:32:43.250 --> 00:32:48.725 align:middle line:84%
the body, not too little,
not too much, just right.

00:32:48.725 --> 00:32:52.190 align:middle line:84%
>> Lots of people want to
showcase themselves through

00:32:52.190 --> 00:32:53.010 align:middle line:90%
social media.

00:32:53.010 --> 00:32:55.538 align:middle line:84%
So they build up this
persona of themselves,

00:32:55.538 --> 00:32:57.080 align:middle line:84%
and they spend a
lot of time crafting

00:32:57.080 --> 00:32:58.790 align:middle line:84%
that persona of
themselves rather than

00:32:58.790 --> 00:33:01.550 align:middle line:84%
actually going out and meeting
people and doing things.

00:33:01.550 --> 00:33:05.450 align:middle line:84%
I think that while it's really
nice to be connected to people

00:33:05.450 --> 00:33:08.360 align:middle line:84%
in different cities,
like family and friends,

00:33:08.360 --> 00:33:12.290 align:middle line:84%
it's not as beneficial to the
people that are around you

00:33:12.290 --> 00:33:16.530 align:middle line:84%
if you're stuck communicating to
people that are not around you.

00:33:16.530 --> 00:33:20.090 align:middle line:84%
>> A lot of the interaction
online is also very brief 10,

00:33:20.090 --> 00:33:22.483 align:middle line:84%
20, 30 seconds, a
few minutes, maybe.

00:33:22.483 --> 00:33:24.650 align:middle line:84%
It's not like sitting down
and having lunch or going

00:33:24.650 --> 00:33:27.140 align:middle line:84%
to the pub and having
a beer where you spend

00:33:27.140 --> 00:33:28.835 align:middle line:90%
a couple of hours together.

00:33:28.835 --> 00:33:33.500 align:middle line:84%
>> Over and over, I hear I
would rather text than talk.

00:33:33.500 --> 00:33:36.770 align:middle line:84%
And what I'm seeing is
that people get so used

00:33:36.770 --> 00:33:39.740 align:middle line:84%
to being shortchanged
out of real conversation,

00:33:39.740 --> 00:33:42.710 align:middle line:84%
so used to getting by
with less that they

00:33:42.710 --> 00:33:45.200 align:middle line:84%
become almost
willing to dispense

00:33:45.200 --> 00:33:46.760 align:middle line:90%
with people altogether.

00:33:46.760 --> 00:33:51.560 align:middle line:10%
>> When you spend less time
interacting face to face with

00:33:51.560 --> 00:33:54.530 align:middle line:10%
individuals, you sort of-- if
we think about that interaction

00:33:54.530 --> 00:33:58.790 align:middle line:10%
as a form of exercise that helps
us know how to communicate with

00:33:58.790 --> 00:34:02.420 align:middle line:10%
the other-- each other and
keep that communication working

00:34:02.420 --> 00:34:05.480 align:middle line:10%
in a healthy way, then we're
not getting as much of that

00:34:05.480 --> 00:34:07.290 align:middle line:10%
exercise as maybe we need.

00:34:07.290 --> 00:34:11.840 align:middle line:84%
And so I do worry, particularly
for younger generations.

00:34:11.840 --> 00:34:13.730 align:middle line:84%
Are they getting
that social exercise

00:34:13.730 --> 00:34:15.650 align:middle line:84%
that they need to learn
how to communicate

00:34:15.650 --> 00:34:16.715 align:middle line:90%
with others in the world?

00:34:16.715 --> 00:34:21.679 align:middle line:84%
>> We did have the advantage
of getting use of a very large

00:34:21.679 --> 00:34:23.060 align:middle line:90%
Canadian survey.

00:34:23.060 --> 00:34:26.537 align:middle line:84%
And they were asked how big is
their network of real friends,

00:34:26.537 --> 00:34:28.370 align:middle line:84%
and they were asked how
big is their network

00:34:28.370 --> 00:34:29.900 align:middle line:90%
of online friends.

00:34:29.900 --> 00:34:33.800 align:middle line:84%
And there was a significant
dose response relationship

00:34:33.800 --> 00:34:36.770 align:middle line:84%
of a positive sort
for real friends.

00:34:36.770 --> 00:34:38.719 align:middle line:84%
The bigger your
network, the more

00:34:38.719 --> 00:34:41.929 align:middle line:84%
satisfied you were with
your life as a whole.

00:34:41.929 --> 00:34:47.480 align:middle line:84%
The effect of the online friends
was either zero or negative.

00:34:47.480 --> 00:34:49.820 align:middle line:84%
And now, the negative one,
you say, how could that be?

00:34:49.820 --> 00:34:52.610 align:middle line:84%
One part it's like
watching television.

00:34:52.610 --> 00:34:55.592 align:middle line:84%
You may like to watch television
and get something out of it,

00:34:55.592 --> 00:34:57.800 align:middle line:84%
but once you get into it,
it's hard to get out of it.

00:34:57.800 --> 00:35:00.290 align:middle line:84%
And then you're finished
the day watching television.

00:35:00.290 --> 00:35:02.750 align:middle line:84%
You've lost all the
opportunity you otherwise had

00:35:02.750 --> 00:35:04.170 align:middle line:90%
to have fun with real people.

00:35:04.170 --> 00:35:06.750 align:middle line:84%
>> I think it can be a tool
for creating community.

00:35:06.750 --> 00:35:08.840 align:middle line:84%
But I don't think it's
the basis of community.

00:35:08.840 --> 00:35:11.510 align:middle line:84%
I think it's very hard
for us as human beings

00:35:11.510 --> 00:35:14.810 align:middle line:90%
to stop with social media.

00:35:14.810 --> 00:35:19.610 align:middle line:84%
I think we do better
when we kind of at least

00:35:19.610 --> 00:35:23.030 align:middle line:84%
see facial contact,
facial recognition,

00:35:23.030 --> 00:35:25.010 align:middle line:90%
even if it is on a screen.

00:35:25.010 --> 00:35:28.610 align:middle line:84%
Making eye contact with somebody
and seeing facial expression,

00:35:28.610 --> 00:35:31.370 align:middle line:84%
seeing gestures is a
very important part

00:35:31.370 --> 00:35:35.280 align:middle line:84%
of our experience of community
and our experience of humanity.

00:35:35.280 --> 00:35:37.790 align:middle line:84%
And I think one of the
challenges with social media

00:35:37.790 --> 00:35:41.450 align:middle line:84%
has been we can talk to the
people who agree with us too

00:35:41.450 --> 00:35:46.490 align:middle line:84%
much, that we can isolate
ourselves into a community

00:35:46.490 --> 00:35:48.950 align:middle line:84%
where we're all talking
about the same thing

00:35:48.950 --> 00:35:52.220 align:middle line:84%
and agreeing with each other
rather than maybe having

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:55.490 align:middle line:84%
differences of opinion and
learning from those differences

00:35:55.490 --> 00:35:57.770 align:middle line:84%
and becoming more
mature and adult

00:35:57.770 --> 00:36:00.480 align:middle line:84%
through those interactions
and differences.

00:36:00.480 --> 00:36:03.470 align:middle line:84%
So I think that's one of
the things I worry about

00:36:03.470 --> 00:36:06.770 align:middle line:84%
with social media and
the isolation it creates

00:36:06.770 --> 00:36:12.980 align:middle line:84%
is that we're going to become
less adult, less informed, less

00:36:12.980 --> 00:36:15.973 align:middle line:90%
human because of that lack of--

00:36:15.973 --> 00:36:17.015 align:middle line:90%
that lack of interaction.

00:36:17.015 --> 00:36:21.020 align:middle line:10%
>> Watching some of the
conversations that within two

00:36:21.020 --> 00:36:24.110 align:middle line:10%
or three comments from something
really interesting to something

00:36:24.110 --> 00:36:28.280 align:middle line:10%
disrespectful and it doesn't
seem to weigh away within

00:36:28.280 --> 00:36:31.760 align:middle line:10%
the culture yet to
keep it positive,

00:36:31.760 --> 00:36:35.360 align:middle line:10%
to keep the discussions
going in a way that enhances

00:36:35.360 --> 00:36:37.770 align:middle line:10%
people's connections
rather than destroys them.

00:36:37.770 --> 00:36:41.060 align:middle line:84%
>> So I am a big proponent
of people actually being able

00:36:41.060 --> 00:36:46.040 align:middle line:84%
to look each other in the eye in
a social situation on a street

00:36:46.040 --> 00:36:49.850 align:middle line:84%
because I do think there is
something profound about that

00:36:49.850 --> 00:36:54.320 align:middle line:84%
eye contact that helps you
understand and empathize with

00:36:54.320 --> 00:37:00.950 align:middle line:84%
another human being that maybe
is lost even with social media

00:37:00.950 --> 00:37:02.660 align:middle line:90%
with a screen experience.

00:37:02.660 --> 00:37:06.760 align:middle line:90%


00:37:06.760 --> 00:37:10.780 align:middle line:84%
>> Over the past 15 years, I've
studied technologies of mobile

00:37:10.780 --> 00:37:12.020 align:middle line:90%
communication.

00:37:12.020 --> 00:37:15.280 align:middle line:84%
And I've interviewed hundreds
and hundreds of people,

00:37:15.280 --> 00:37:18.610 align:middle line:84%
young and old, about
their plugged-in lives.

00:37:18.610 --> 00:37:22.480 align:middle line:10%
And what I've found is
that our little devices,

00:37:22.480 --> 00:37:25.000 align:middle line:10%
those little devices
in our pockets,

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:28.900 align:middle line:10%
are so psychologically
powerful that they don't only

00:37:28.900 --> 00:37:31.120 align:middle line:10%
change what we do.

00:37:31.120 --> 00:37:32.848 align:middle line:90%
They change who we are.

00:37:32.848 --> 00:37:35.140 align:middle line:84%
>> Technology has kind of
stripped away everything that

00:37:35.140 --> 00:37:38.183 align:middle line:84%
we would think of as far as
having day-to-day community.

00:37:38.183 --> 00:37:40.600 align:middle line:84%
There's not going to be any
more coming to the coffee shop

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:41.110 align:middle line:90%
and just sit.

00:37:41.110 --> 00:37:42.520 align:middle line:84%
If you walk into a
coffee shop right now,

00:37:42.520 --> 00:37:44.930 align:middle line:84%
there's small groups of people
sitting close to each other,

00:37:44.930 --> 00:37:46.180 align:middle line:84%
looking at their phones,
and everyone else just

00:37:46.180 --> 00:37:47.680 align:middle line:84%
has their computer
in front of them.

00:37:47.680 --> 00:37:51.010 align:middle line:84%
>> Becoming immersed in
our own echo chambers,

00:37:51.010 --> 00:37:55.600 align:middle line:84%
our own curated online world
can lead to real-life community

00:37:55.600 --> 00:37:56.980 align:middle line:90%
breakdown.

00:37:56.980 --> 00:37:59.200 align:middle line:84%
We rarely interact
online with those

00:37:59.200 --> 00:38:01.210 align:middle line:84%
who are different
from us, and this

00:38:01.210 --> 00:38:03.280 align:middle line:84%
can contribute to
social ignorance

00:38:03.280 --> 00:38:06.730 align:middle line:90%
and foster mistrust in others.

00:38:06.730 --> 00:38:10.810 align:middle line:84%
Trust is an essential
component of happiness.

00:38:10.810 --> 00:38:13.000 align:middle line:10%
Research tells us
that the more we

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:16.960 align:middle line:10%
feel we can trust those around
us, ranging from our neighbors

00:38:16.960 --> 00:38:22.260 align:middle line:10%
to complete strangers, the
more life satisfaction we have.

00:38:22.260 --> 00:38:25.140 align:middle line:84%
Intrigued by this question
of how much we trust those

00:38:25.140 --> 00:38:27.960 align:middle line:84%
around us, researcher
John Helliwell

00:38:27.960 --> 00:38:31.620 align:middle line:84%
often includes this question
in his happiness surveys.

00:38:31.620 --> 00:38:33.930 align:middle line:84%
If you dropped your
wallet, how likely

00:38:33.930 --> 00:38:35.940 align:middle line:84%
is it that it would
be returned to you?

00:38:35.940 --> 00:38:36.990 align:middle line:90%
>> Almost nil.

00:38:36.990 --> 00:38:38.780 align:middle line:90%
>> I'd say 50/50.

00:38:38.780 --> 00:38:42.000 align:middle line:84%
It could go either way
depending on who will find it.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:43.150 align:middle line:90%
>> No, I don't think so.

00:38:43.150 --> 00:38:43.950 align:middle line:90%
I don't think so.

00:38:43.950 --> 00:38:45.225 align:middle line:90%
[SPEAKING SIMULTANEOUSLY]

00:38:45.225 --> 00:38:46.800 align:middle line:90%
>> Neighborhood dependent.

00:38:46.800 --> 00:38:47.600 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah.

00:38:47.600 --> 00:38:49.440 align:middle line:90%
>> Highly unlikely.

00:38:49.440 --> 00:38:50.290 align:middle line:90%
>> Highly unlikely?

00:38:50.290 --> 00:38:51.270 align:middle line:90%
>> Like 20%.

00:38:51.270 --> 00:38:52.933 align:middle line:90%
>> 5%.

00:38:52.933 --> 00:38:54.100 align:middle line:90%
>> You wouldn't get it back.

00:38:54.100 --> 00:38:55.570 align:middle line:90%
>> Yeah, not likely.

00:38:55.570 --> 00:38:56.790 align:middle line:90%
>> I don't know.

00:38:56.790 --> 00:38:59.723 align:middle line:84%
I want to expect the
best from people.

00:38:59.723 --> 00:39:01.140 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's
important as well

00:39:01.140 --> 00:39:04.352 align:middle line:90%
to have that state of mind.

00:39:04.352 --> 00:39:06.060 align:middle line:84%
That's what makes a
community, basically.

00:39:06.060 --> 00:39:08.190 align:middle line:84%
It's the spirit,
but I'm not sure

00:39:08.190 --> 00:39:09.780 align:middle line:90%
if-- it depends on the person.

00:39:09.780 --> 00:39:12.900 align:middle line:10%
>> It's someone in an experiment
to gauge the level of honesty

00:39:12.900 --> 00:39:16.980 align:middle line:10%
and trust in a big city in
2009, the "Toronto Star"

00:39:16.980 --> 00:39:20.760 align:middle line:10%
dropped 20 wallets around the
greater Toronto area and waited

00:39:20.760 --> 00:39:23.310 align:middle line:10%
to see how many
would be returned.

00:39:23.310 --> 00:39:29.220 align:middle line:10%
Each wallet contained $43.77,
a photo ID, a phone number,

00:39:29.220 --> 00:39:33.410 align:middle line:10%
some pictures, and a grocery
list, amongst other things.

00:39:33.410 --> 00:39:36.020 align:middle line:90%
The results were fascinating.

00:39:36.020 --> 00:39:40.370 align:middle line:84%
>> So 23% thought it
would be returned.

00:39:40.370 --> 00:39:42.960 align:middle line:84%
80% of the wallets
were returned.

00:39:42.960 --> 00:39:46.670 align:middle line:84%
So I often say we're just
shooting ourselves in our foot

00:39:46.670 --> 00:39:52.760 align:middle line:84%
by thinking as ill of our
fellow men and woman as we do.

00:39:52.760 --> 00:39:54.980 align:middle line:90%
And why is that?

00:39:54.980 --> 00:40:01.020 align:middle line:84%
And one reason is that
what you read in the media,

00:40:01.020 --> 00:40:03.920 align:middle line:84%
in fact, is about this
is supposed to be,

00:40:03.920 --> 00:40:06.650 align:middle line:84%
in fact, what they still
teach in journalism schools is

00:40:06.650 --> 00:40:07.940 align:middle line:90%
that bad news sells.

00:40:07.940 --> 00:40:11.330 align:middle line:84%
So bad news is when
bad people do something

00:40:11.330 --> 00:40:13.190 align:middle line:84%
bad to other
people, and then you

00:40:13.190 --> 00:40:15.050 align:middle line:84%
begin to think it's
much more common than it

00:40:15.050 --> 00:40:17.008 align:middle line:84%
is because that's all
the newspapers are about.

00:40:17.008 --> 00:40:19.790 align:middle line:84%
You don't read about the
good turns people do.

00:40:19.790 --> 00:40:22.880 align:middle line:84%
So you underestimate
the ability of other,

00:40:22.880 --> 00:40:25.670 align:middle line:84%
and that's terribly destructive
of social relations,

00:40:25.670 --> 00:40:27.510 align:middle line:84%
terribly destructive
of happiness,

00:40:27.510 --> 00:40:28.850 align:middle line:90%
got to be turned around.

00:40:28.850 --> 00:40:32.030 align:middle line:84%
>> Fear is our most
basic human emotion.

00:40:32.030 --> 00:40:36.890 align:middle line:84%
And so to appeal to
fear is obviously

00:40:36.890 --> 00:40:39.530 align:middle line:90%
a very effective strategy.

00:40:39.530 --> 00:40:45.140 align:middle line:84%
And we have sort of
a natural inclination

00:40:45.140 --> 00:40:52.160 align:middle line:84%
to also group and to distinguish
whether someone's in my group

00:40:52.160 --> 00:40:54.300 align:middle line:90%
or not in my group.

00:40:54.300 --> 00:40:58.790 align:middle line:84%
And so when we use fear to
sort of promote that tendency,

00:40:58.790 --> 00:41:01.170 align:middle line:90%
that can be quite problematic.

00:41:01.170 --> 00:41:02.240 align:middle line:90%
>> So you're excited.

00:41:02.240 --> 00:41:03.260 align:middle line:84%
How do you think
your neighbors are

00:41:03.260 --> 00:41:05.330 align:middle line:84%
going to feel coming
together and interacting

00:41:05.330 --> 00:41:06.530 align:middle line:90%
with each other?

00:41:06.530 --> 00:41:10.360 align:middle line:84%
>> I think it's going to be
a really valuable experience

00:41:10.360 --> 00:41:11.160 align:middle line:90%
for everyone.

00:41:11.160 --> 00:41:14.410 align:middle line:84%
I don't really know
the level of knowing

00:41:14.410 --> 00:41:16.160 align:middle line:84%
people have of each
other in the building,

00:41:16.160 --> 00:41:18.230 align:middle line:84%
so it'll be a good
experiment for me

00:41:18.230 --> 00:41:20.780 align:middle line:90%
to see how everyone interacts.

00:41:20.780 --> 00:41:22.190 align:middle line:90%
And yeah, I'm excited.

00:41:22.190 --> 00:41:24.890 align:middle line:90%


00:41:24.890 --> 00:41:25.970 align:middle line:90%
What do you say?

00:41:25.970 --> 00:41:28.737 align:middle line:84%
Let's just backtrack to
the individual person.

00:41:28.737 --> 00:41:30.320 align:middle line:84%
Let's say, right
now, there's somebody

00:41:30.320 --> 00:41:33.770 align:middle line:84%
who's feeling less
community oriented,

00:41:33.770 --> 00:41:35.390 align:middle line:84%
feeling socially
isolated, feeling

00:41:35.390 --> 00:41:38.420 align:middle line:84%
like their social
networks have dwindled.

00:41:38.420 --> 00:41:42.798 align:middle line:84%
What do you tell
that person to do?

00:41:42.798 --> 00:41:46.120 align:middle line:84%
>> I think it's mostly to
try to get a sense of how

00:41:46.120 --> 00:41:49.660 align:middle line:90%
they're spending their time now.

00:41:49.660 --> 00:41:51.610 align:middle line:84%
Are they in the
right neighborhood?

00:41:51.610 --> 00:41:56.110 align:middle line:84%
Is it a place that that's
where they can find enough time

00:41:56.110 --> 00:41:57.490 align:middle line:90%
to reach out to others?

00:41:57.490 --> 00:42:00.280 align:middle line:84%
And what are the
institutions where

00:42:00.280 --> 00:42:03.340 align:middle line:84%
they may be able to meet
others or serve others?

00:42:03.340 --> 00:42:09.730 align:middle line:10%
>> I think sport is this
absolutely incredibly important

00:42:09.730 --> 00:42:11.390 align:middle line:10%
element of our society.

00:42:11.390 --> 00:42:13.600 align:middle line:90%
And I think we can't--

00:42:13.600 --> 00:42:16.690 align:middle line:84%
I can't overemphasize the
importance of the recreation

00:42:16.690 --> 00:42:20.290 align:middle line:84%
department in a city
and their ability

00:42:20.290 --> 00:42:23.180 align:middle line:84%
to get people to get out
there and play together.

00:42:23.180 --> 00:42:25.340 align:middle line:84%
It's a wonderful way to
build a sense of community.

00:42:25.340 --> 00:42:27.173 align:middle line:84%
It's a wonderful way
to keep people healthy.

00:42:27.173 --> 00:42:30.400 align:middle line:84%
>> A lot of folks who work in
sort of the social development

00:42:30.400 --> 00:42:34.630 align:middle line:84%
field would suggest that you
